        "observed_type": "section_header",
        "canon_role": "section_header",
        "text": "Structure of a Skeletal Muscle",
        "bbox": [
          0.518796997488087,
          0.6438492065405613,
          0.6954887212149203,
          0.6526162787110612
        ],
        "order": 49
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_bio-113065.pdf_213_55",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Muscle fiber",
        "bbox": [
          0.8383458640402559,
          0.6991279072089365,
          0.8966165400324259,
          0.7063953487503659
        ],
        "order": 56
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_bio-113065.pdf_213_18",
        "observed_type": "caption",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Figure 6.3.4: This figure shows major skeletal muscles in the back (posterior) of the body.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1052631532894738,
          0.7571924602657877,
          0.4736842059210528,
          0.7790697672476721
        ],
        "order": 58
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_bio-113065.pdf_213_57",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Tendon",
        "bbox": [
          0.5733082718461758,
          0.7950581396398958,
          0.610902255409463,
          0.8023255811813252
        ],
        "order": 63
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_bio-113065.pdf_213_39",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "To move bones in opposite directions, skeletal muscles often consist of muscle pairs that work in opposition to one another. For example, when the biceps muscle (on the front of the upper arm) contracts, it can cause the elbow joint to flex or bend the arm, as shown in Figure 6.3.5. When the triceps muscle (on the back of the upper arm) contracts, it can cause the elbow to extend or straighten the arm. The",
        "bbox": [
          0.08458646106672946,
          0.8066860465049611,
          0.4943609090538846,
          0.8938953488438763
        ],
        "order": 64
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_bio-113065.pdf_213_60",
        "observed_type": "caption",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Figure 6.3.6: Each skeletal muscle has a structure of bundles within bundles. Bundles of muscle fibers make up a muscle fascicle, and fascicles' bundles make up a skeletal muscle. At each level of bundling, a connective tissue membrane surrounds the bundle. The muscle cells, fascicle, and the whole muscle are surrounded by Endomysium, perimysium, and epimysium, respectively. All connective tissues merge together to make a tendon that attaches the muscle to bones.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5244360840852132,
          0.8110119048120765,
          0.8947368431077695,
          0.9013036458664139
        ],
        "order": 65
      }
    ]
  },
